== Controlling PIVX ==

Run ''pivxd'' or ''pivx-qt -server''. You can control it via the command-line pivx-cli utility or by [http://json-rpc.org/wiki/specification HTTP JSON-RPC] commands.

You must create a pivx.conf configuration file setting an rpcuser and rpcpassword; see [[Running PIVX]] for details.

Now run:
  $ ./pivxd -daemon
  PIVX server starting
  $ ./pivx-cli -rpcwait help
  # shows the help text

A [[API Calls list|list of RPC calls]] will be shown.

  $ ./pivx-cli getbalance
  2000.00000

If you are learning the API, it is a very good idea to use the test network (run pivxd -testnet and pivx-cli -testnet).

== JSON-RPC ==

Running PIVX with the -server argument (or running pivxd) tells it to function as a [http://json-rpc.org/wiki/specification HTTP JSON-RPC] server, but
[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_access_authentication Basic access authentication] must be used when communicating with it, and, for security, by default, the server only accepts connections from other processes on the same machine.  If your HTTP or JSON library requires you to specify which 'realm' is authenticated, use 'jsonrpc'.

Allowing arbitrary machines to access the JSON-RPC port (using the rpcallowip [[Running PIVX|configuration option]]) is dangerous and '''strongly discouraged'''-- access should be strictly limited to trusted machines.

To access the server you should find a [http://json-rpc.org/wiki/implementations suitable library] for your language.

